Notes:

Date: 0/0/1874
Source: Edward Crewe
Author: BAINES
Vol / Page: 176
Edition:
Quote: When all was completed I had one hundred logs rolled into the stream below, and thirty above  the dam. I then fixed upon a day and an hour to have a `drive,' and mustered all the men I could.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1894
Source: NZ Official Yearbook
Author:
Vol / Page: 331
Edition:
Quote: Often it is necessary to construct costly dams to impound the water in the upper parts of the creek, in order that it may be suddenly liberated ... so that the entire assemblage [332] of [kauri] logs may be `driven' to the booms. In dry seasons the logs may remain in the bed of the creek for months, and, occasionally, after a successful `drive', the harvest of logs is carried out tosea and lost, through the booms breaking from the immense pressure behind them.
Notes: (T. Kirk)

Date: 0/0/1889
Source: Forest Flora
Author: KIRK
Vol / Page: 151
Edition:
Quote:  ... [the booms] often enclose an area of several acres, which after a successful `drive,' is crowded with thousands of logs.
Notes:

